{"parse":{"title":"Necropolitics","pageid":51427743,"revid":858576266,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Necropolitics</b> is the use of <a href=\"/wiki/Power_(social_and_political)\" title=\"Power (social and political)\">social and political power</a> to dictate how some people may live and how some must die. <a href=\"/wiki/Achille_Mbembe\" title=\"Achille Mbembe\">Achille Mbembe</a>, author of <i><a href=\"/wiki/On_the_Postcolony\" title=\"On the Postcolony\">On the Postcolony</a></i>, was the first scholar to explore the term in depth in his article of the same name.<sup id=\"cite_ref-mbembe_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-mbembe-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>  Necropolitics is often discussed with <a href=\"/wiki/Biopower\" title=\"Biopower\">biopower</a>, the <a href=\"/wiki/Foucauldian\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Foucauldian\">Foucauldian</a> term for the use of social and political power to control people's lives.\n</p><p>Mbembe was clear that necropolitics is more than a right to kill (Foucault's <i>droit de glaive</i>), but also the right to expose other people (including a country's own citizens) to death. His view of necropolitics also included the right to impose <a href=\"/wiki/Social_death\" title=\"Social death\">social</a> or <a href=\"/wiki/Civil_death\" title=\"Civil death\">civil death</a>, the right to enslave others, and other forms of <a href=\"/wiki/Political_violence\" title=\"Political violence\">political violence</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-mbembe_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-mbembe-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Necropolitics is a theory of the walking dead, namely a way of analysing how \"contemporary forms of subjugation of life to the power of death\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-mbembe_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-mbembe-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> forces some bodies to remain in different states of being located between life and death. Mbembe uses the examples of slavery, apartheid, the colonisation of Palestine and the figure of the suicide bomber to show how different forms of necropower over the body (statist, racialised, a state of exception, urgency, martyrdom) reduce people to precarious conditions of life.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Queer_necropolitics\">Queer necropolitics</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Necropolitics&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Queer necropolitics\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/Jasbir_Puar\" title=\"Jasbir Puar\">Jasbir Puar</a> coined the term <i>queer necropolitics</i> to analyze the <a href=\"/wiki/Post-9/11\" title=\"Post-9/11\">post-9/11</a> queer outrage regarding <a href=\"/wiki/Gay_bashing\" title=\"Gay bashing\">gay bashing</a> and simultaneous queer complicity with <a href=\"/wiki/Islamophobia\" title=\"Islamophobia\">Islamophobia</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Many scholars use Puar's queer necropolics in conjunction with <a href=\"/wiki/Judith_Butler\" title=\"Judith Butler\">Judith Butler</a>'s concept of a grievable life.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> Queer necropolitics is the subject of an anthology from <a href=\"/wiki/Routledge\" title=\"Routledge\">Routledge</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Necropolitics&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-mbembe-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-mbembe_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-mbembe_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-mbembe_1-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\"><a href=\"/wiki/Achille_Mbembe\" title=\"Achille Mbembe\">Mbembe, Achille</a> (2003). \"Necropolitics\". <i>Public Culture</i>. <b>15</b> (1): 11\u201340.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Public+Culture&amp;rft.atitle=Necropolitics&amp;rft.volume=15&amp;rft.issue=1&amp;rft.pages=11-40&amp;rft.date=2003&amp;rft.aulast=Mbembe&amp;rft.aufirst=Achille&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ANecropolitics\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Puar, Jasbir K. (2007). <i>Terrorist assemblages&#160;: homonationalism in queer times</i>. Durham: Duke University Press. pp.&#160;32\u201379. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780822340942\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9780822340942\">9780822340942</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Terrorist+assemblages+%3A+homonationalism+in+queer+times&amp;rft.place=Durham&amp;rft.pages=32-79&amp;rft.pub=Duke+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2007&amp;rft.isbn=9780822340942&amp;rft.aulast=Puar&amp;rft.aufirst=Jasbir+K.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ANecropolitics\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#ci